    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Central Park Terror: The Outcry</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Peter Aronson letter on mob violence against women in Central Park says while individual police officers need to be investigated, Police Department itself should also be closely scrutinized</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Inquiry Focuses on Officers' Responses to Violence in Park After Parade'' (news article, June 14):</p>
        <p>While individual police officers need to be investigated after the mob violence in Central Park, the Police Department itself should also be closely scrutinized.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Inquiry Focuses on Officers' Responses to Violence in Park After Parade'' (news article, June 14):</p>
        <p>While individual police officers need to be investigated after the mob violence in Central Park, the Police Department itself should also be closely scrutinized.</p>
        <p>I was in the park between 5:30 and 6 p.m., trying to ride my bike north from 59th Street. I saw no violence, but I saw crowds of young people, more men than women, walking on the road, and only two police officers walking among them. I saw clumps of officers at different points along the road.</p>
        <p>With officers apparently instructed to remain on the side and not patrol within the huge crowd, it is clear how a large group could surround an individual and obscure an attack. Why were the officers instructed to stand on the side?</p>
        <p>PETER ARONSON  New York, June 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
